ull, Yorkshire, England","Kidale, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Cleveland, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Percy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"Ernald","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Fernel</b>, itself a shortened form of a derivative of Old French <i>ferron</i> ‘blacksmith, ironmonger’.","History: This surname was brought to North America from England. It is listed along with its original form <i>Fernel</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":17,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":27,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":37,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Ernald II de Percy was born in 1069, in Stokesley, Yorkshire, England as the son of Ernald I de Percy and Mrs Ernald I de Percy. He married Mrs Ernald II de Percy before 1105, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1140, in Cleveland, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1069–1140":"1069–1140","–Female":"Surnud","1105–1179":"1105–1179","1038–1096":"1038–1096","before 1105":"enne 1105","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1038":"1038","1069":"1069","before 1069":"enne 1069","1179":"1179","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","Europe":"Europe","Stokesley, Yorkshire, England":"Stokesley, Yorkshire, England","Bridport, Dorset, England":"Bridport, Dorset, England","Hull, Yorkshire, England":"Hull, Yorkshire, England","Kidale, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Cleveland, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1069–1140":"1069–1140","–Female":"Kuollut","1105–1179":"1105–1179","1038–1096":"1038–1096","before 1105":"ennen vuotta 1105","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1038":"1038","1069":"1069","before 1069":"ennen vuotta 1069","1179":"1179","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1